I&#39;m pretty sure there&#39;s a bug in the current JUnit 4.  Running this 
example with the built-in Runner does the right thing (see 
AnnotationTest.NonStaticOneTimeSetup): it adds a descriptive failure 
saying that @BeforeClass must annotate a static method.  But the 
JUnit4TestAdapter (for running JUnit 4 tests using the JUnit 3.x runner) 
doesn&#39;t perform this check.

Thanks for the example--it also totally confuses my Eclipse/JUnit 4 
runner, so I&#39;ll have to fix that as well.

    David Saff

